You were talking about the minimum wage.
Do you think that other federal controls are more strict now than they used to be in the past?
Oh, yes.
Definitely.
What did they regulate, if anything?
What?
What kind of things did they use to regulate?
Well, just who it was.
Say this way.
Suppose I want, just like this woman that I've got working for me, suppose I'd want somebody to work for me, and I'd say, I'll give you $6 this week to work for me.
And maybe somebody over here, they'd tell somebody, I'll give you $3 to come.
That's no regulation.
And it was the same way with any kind of business or anything, just whatever the individual, and especially on ranches.
One would pay one thing and another another, and they'd say, well, I've got a job.
I'm not going to give up my job thinking I can go over there and maybe I'll get cut off.
And now it's regulated what they've got to do.
They've got to pay a minimum wage now.
I don't care what it is.
Do you think that's better?
Sure, it's better.
Look, two years ago, in the stores here, you know what they paid?
$1.75 an hour to stand on their feet all day long, eight hours.
Well, now they've got to pay that minimum wage.
And don't you think it's better?
Yes, I do.
I think it is.
Well, now, all right, if you say this way, all right, I've got a big farm out here.
Now, you come out here, Gary, and I'll give you $1.75 an hour to work all day.
All right, somebody over here, they'll say, well, I'll give you $2.30.
Well, you see, there's no regularity.
There's no system to that.
That's just gee-haw about where you'd say, well, I've got this job, and I don't want to quit it.
Because I go over here and I know I can work on him.
Oh, yes.
It's definitely better.
Well, what do you think about the way they're trying to control the economy with the wage and, I mean, with the price controls?
Do you think they should keep up the price controls that they've been enforcing upon certain goods?
Well, I'll tell you.
That's kind of a hard question, but it's this way.
I think it depends largely on what that it is.
I think that farmers, I don't think there ought to be anything controlled with what they have worked for.
It costs a lot to raise cattle.
It costs a lot to raise feed.
And I think they ought to be allowed to sell it for what they can get for it.
